<TITLE> HC orders Dhaka rivers cleared by November </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Jan 24 (bdnews24.com)The High Court on Sunday ordered the government to begin demolishing all illegal structures built on the banks of the four rivers surrounding Dhaka citythe Buriganga, Turag, Sitalakhya and Baluwithin the next month. It also directed the government to complete the clearance of all the unauthorised installations by Nov 30 this year, and submit a written report on compliance. The court order also required the authorities to submit a quarterly written progress report on the removal of the illegal structures to the Supreme Court registrar. A two-member High Court bench comprising justices Syed Mahmud Hossain and Kamrul Islam Siddiqui gave the order Sunday gave the orders on a public interest petition filed by local NGO Human Rights and Peace for Bangladesh. The same High Court bench on May 24 last year had ordered the government to take effective measures to save the rivers flowing around Dhaka city. On Jun 4, it asked the deputy commissioners of Dhaka, Narayanganj, Munshiganj and Gazipur to notify the court of the steps taken to thwart pollution, river-bed filling and encroachment by illegal structures on the banks of the four rivers and how much time they would require to accomplish the tasks. The two judges on June 8 summoned the deputy commissioners of Dhaka, Narayanganj, Munshiganj and Gazipur, the chief executive officer of Dhaka City Corporation, WASA managing director and director of land surveys to report on the matter. On Jun 25 the same bench issued a number of directives to the government in a bid to save the four rivers, including demacation of the river banks and removal of illegal installations built on those banks. bdnew
